      <div class="item__2" data-animate="fade-up">
        <div class="cs-ntr wrapper_ntr">
          <p data-animate="fade-up">
            <strong>Challenge</strong>
          </p>
          <h6 data-animate="fade-up">Making the visible invisible.</h6>
          <p data-animate="fade-up">
            QR codes are functional, precise and often unobtrusive. Art should be visible, tangible and surprising. The challenge was to translate the logic of coded systems into an independent visual system for exhibition communication without losing conceptual complexity. The custom-developed display typeface PICA condenses this idea into a coded yet sensorial visual language.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="item__3" data-animate="fade-up">
        {% lazypicture "tghb_artshow_cc__04.jpg", "Perspective exhibition - dark poster close-up" %}
      </div>

      <div class="item__4" data-animate="fade-up">
        <div class="cs-ntr wrapper_ntr">
          <p data-animate="fade-up">
            <strong>Approach</strong>
          </p>
          <h6 data-animate="fade-up">Angular instead of round. Precise and compact.</h6>
          <p data-animate="fade-up">
            The typeface PICA is based on QR-code aesthetics: built from squares, circles and lines, compact, precise and distinctive. The result is a recognizable type design for poster design, graphic communication and spatial applications in an exhibition context.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
